text:
Goodness me, so many negative comments on here from their marriage to moving.
Look, sometimes people build beautiful houses and settle for life, sometimes they get their first house (and I say first house because this is free standing) and live in it and see the things that they want or need and even get that renovation bug - it‚Äôs jussstttt like the travel bug . My husband and I brought our first house, renovated and we adored it, people couldn‚Äôt understand when we sold. But that was always the aim. We brought another house and we‚Äôre currently knocking it down and rebuilding. We may stay there for a long time we may on sell. Don‚Äôt know yet. Sometimes people enjoy the process of renovating and moving, and to be quite honest, if we didn‚Äôt sell our house I‚Äôd be changing it up because the me that started renovating have little to no idea, but the me now is very focussed and knows what she likes, much like Lydia (and yes we painted the house 3 times in 10 years!) . Gosh my mum didn‚Äôt move a lot but far out she changed up the house so much. So basically all I‚Äôm saying is, you don‚Äôt know, you see a snippet, people are different. text: I feel like you and Ali should get ducks. I know you‚Äôve talked about chickens before, and I agree, but I think you would enjoy the absolute hell out of ducks. They‚Äôre absolutely hilarious, they get on with dogs well, and their eggs are excellent for baking. Actually all waterfowl eggs are excellent for baking, for whatever reason they lend an extra kind of fluffiness to baking that normal eggs do not. Plus, ducklings bond with whoever they see first upon hatching so if a duckling bonds with you, it will literally follow you everywhere like a little feathered puppy. They also eat garden pests, like slugs and other nasties that might eat your beautiful produce. Just some food for thought. P.S I LOVE the silk sleeveless lemon dress on you. text: Oh no I assumed because you loved The Holiday you had experienced the whole Nancy Meyers catalogue. As a designer I had many clients asking me to design their house like "that movie with Diane Keaton and Jack Nicholson". I was obsessed with that house too so knew exactly how to deliver their brief. My friend and I have watched it so many times we joke we could play each of the roles. Not sure if Kelly told you but the deli they go to when they are all shopping for dinner is Ina Garten's original famous deli and where her brand, The Barefoot Contessa, started. If you look back at it you'll see the deli bags hanging on the wall with her brand. Now I'm not going to assume you've watched "Its Complicated", another of Nancy's films. Meryl Streep's house and bakery in that are divine too. Watch that if you haven't already. On a trip to America I  actually hunted down the location of that house and drove past and soaked up the absolutely beautiful area it is in. That East Coast style of America you mentioned is very influenced from the English country style simply because its origins are English but now with their history and lifestyle giving it its own spin. Nancy's daughter wrote and directed "Home Alone" with Reece Witherspoon. You can see the influence, aesthetic and talent her mother has passed on. That house is a really lovely experience too! Lots to watch, enjoy! Oh and if you haven't watched any of The Barefoot Contessa cooking shows they are fab. I've lost many days escaping into Ina's kitchen. You'll fall in love with her and Jeffrey they are such a beautiful couple.
author: Di Hendy

The Highclere estate is beautiful there are some stunning lakes to walk around (easiest to drive to) and there are also beautiful Coachouses you can stay in. text: This has got to be my all-time favorite vlog of yours. You have been so honest and genuine in explaining your life and how much you have grown and changed as a woman, a wife, and a mother to your fur babies. The personal conversation you shared at the end of this blog was so beautiful, heartwarming, heartfelt, and sincere. I honestly felt like I was right there in the room with you, listening to a close friend share her innermost thoughts. When your eyes welled with tears, so did mine. No one on this platform, or any other, has ever made me feel that way. You are still so young and to have achieved this level of maturity is truly amazing and inspiring. I am 60 years old and I know people my age who have not obtained this much. Your parents must be incredibly proud of you (and Ali as well). I am proud of you and feel as though I have known you all my life. God bless you and your family. Stay safe.
author: Sherry Copeland

text:
Before the pandemic we never really had the time to stop and think about where we are going, what we want? Are we missing out?
Once the pandemic hit and we had to 'reorganise' we way we live and the way we do things, it became apparent that some wants and needs were unnecessary and there were things we could do without and things that had more priority because they had more meaning in our lives! The stuff we once held dear were meaningless....so we discarded them. A simpler way of life beckoned and it felt good. Holding family and love ones dear were the priority, mental wellness was the priority, a sense of calm and stillness in what was the frenetic, commercial world was the priority. Thus we learned who we are, what we truly want our of life and lived it.

text: Hello Lydia, I truly love watching your videos but there is one thing you mentioned that caught my attention and I would like to share my thoughts on it. The masseter muscle Botox treatment. I am very delighted to hear that it has worked wonders for you. Headaches are really awful and the fact that you have been able to dramatically reduce your paracetamol use is amazing. However, I think it‚Äôs worth thinking about more natural options: especially as you mentioned that people close to you have decided to go for Botox. It‚Äôs important to remember that we are all different and Botox may not be essential for each individual (invasive).. better to have an assessment first. It could simply be tension of the face/jaw/neck or issues with the joints of these areas which are causing a misalignment in the upper body thereby causing extra tension. As an osteopath myself I would highly recommend anyone with jaw tension to try a more natural route like osteopathy or chiropractic before jumping into Botox.

text: ***Dear dear Lydia I‚Äôm oozing the countryside grandma thingy, didn‚Äôt even now I was. I am a real grandma and only discovered YouTube videos  during the 1st lock down! I realise every day is perfect now. So I make myself look absolutely lovely every single day. I get the best comments. One of our new starters at work said I‚Äôm the best dress women she has ever seen, I‚Äôm 30 years older than her!  My tiny garden (yard) is currently full of potatoes,peas, tomatoes, raspberries, lettuce, strawberries, rhubarb, chives and some herbs. My clothes I buy from H&M, Arket, oasis, cos and other high street so it can be done on a smaller budget Lydia you are right I‚Äôm living proof of it. text: I think one reason why people get frustrated about you promoting this life-style is not so much money (event though they make it about it) but time. It also comes from your content creating job : we see you making hour-long walks with your dogs , playing dress-up, gardening and cooking... All of this things can be really therapeutic but you need to have time for them every day. You talk about journeys and you have obviously grown from a place where you had no team or almost, had to work countless hours to build a situation where you can afford to take that time, and big bonus it contributes to your job. But would you have imagined this life-style when you where drowned under work every single day, wondering if you were going to make it as a content creator ? Wouldn't you have been frustrated if someone had come and told you that you just had to shift your state of mind when you were at your lowest ?

text: Personally I'm inspired by you, your style and your outlook on life. I live in an urban area surrounded by other houses but I flounce around in pretty dresses because you inspired me to embrace my feminine side. I take care of my garden and grow things because I find it relaxing. Even when I had a flat I had plants on my balcony and indoor plants. Now I live in a house and my children are older, I've got myself a puppy because I always wanted one and I see how much joy animals can bring. I can't justify buying hermes bags but I'll sure as hell find dupes for your luxury items so I can wear the looks I like. These things are very much in our heads, comparison is the thief of joy. One person's success does not represent the absence of your own. Meet yourself where you are and work from there. As women we should applaud each other because we go through way too much to not support each other. Never apologise for living your life and being happy.

text: Just the other day I was talking to my mother about you, your life and journey, and how wonderful it is to tag along how we all change and grow throughout the years. It at times helps me to get perspective in my own life to see the changes and growth I've done myself. We sometimes don't realise our own journey as we are too busy living, but following you through the years and see the changes in your life gives me possibilities to reflect on my own life as well. It's like a little extra bonus that comes with following you. My mother grew up in the countryside in our homeland and here in Sweden we always lived next to the woods, so living "in" nature has been a constant in my life. I now live right next to a forest as a grown-up. As refugees we didn't have much but we got to experience the richness of nature and all her gifts. Even now on clear nights I still fill up in wonder as I look up at the stars. Waking up with an amazing sunrise fills the spirit and seeing the dew on the grass is magical - it literally costs nothing to feel awestruck and lucky to be alive!

text: I am currently interning to be a social worker in the states! The agency I intern at use this model called the resilience model. And what we are talking about this week in group therapy is exactly what you are describing. It's called stories in my head. It's this idea that we have our own perception of reality. And sometimes that perception can really hold us back. Sometimes it's our amygdala protecting us, even if it's not a true threat. Sometimes we have had horrible and negative experiences which cause us to make up stories or make assumptions about how something is going to go. It's a real effort to flip the script and not allow the stories in our head to hold us back from having hard conversations or doing things we want to do

text: I really appreciate your discussion about basically a positive or negative outlook. After I first started watching your channel, I shared your thinking around luxury (not being based on money) with a friend who tends towards negativity, because it spoke to me so much, and really stated so well how I think about life. She responded exactly how you are sharing. I also wonder why?? Why can't she see the "luxury" of her own life, or her ability to create luxury out of the things she loves. I see your genuine enjoyment of all things, not just expensive items. And, you are truly genuine in your awe of expensive things (I LOVE your "oh wow"s all of the time, and especially during your tour of your London hotel room!!), and not a blase kind of response. But your "oh wow"s for seeing your seeds sprout are just as excited as they are for expensive things. Your morning walks, and excitement for the beauty of the nature around you, the sunrise, all are so genuine, and show a zest for life, and an appreciation of all life offers. I agree; I feel sorry for people who can't seem to find that joy, and who seem to just want to be our killjoys. It does work for them occasionally;  it would feel like a gut punch to me, like it did to you, until I also realized it's from their unhappiness and jealousy. It still stings occasionally. But, I have learned to realize how much happier I am getting equally excited about the smell of freshly cut grass, a beautiful cloud formation, and the amazing piece of jewelry I just purchased.  I'm happy to hear that you are in a healthy place to respond, and I appreciate that you are also genuinely concerned about their unhappiness.

text: Regarding the lifestyle comments.. here's the thing:  everyone evolves in their own time.  It can take a whole lifetime for some people to realize their own relationship with what they want out of life, with what they want from their relationship with money, and what they CHOOSE for their life.  I just retired from 25 years with the state as an IT Analyst at a local university, and pension life is scary!!  But, I've realized that my mindset can set me free... I don't need to buy something everyday (like I did when I was working full time), I don't need to buy something right now - today (like I did when I was working), and there was a huge cost to working outside my home every day.  I am so much happier now, taking care of my home and garden and pursing creativity on the side.  But I'm a broke a** lady now! ;-)  People need to come to terms with their own choices in their own time... most of the 'negativity' that you are getting, are the ripples of frustration from folks who don't know how to live the life they want.  You've come a long way in your confidence journey, and maybe watching your journey will inspire others to help with their journey.  Gardening, in particular can be done anywhere... except at my house, where the deer and rabbits eat everything not covered with cage cloches... lol.   You're making a hugely positive difference in the world, Lydia... keep up the awesome work! ;-)

text: Whilst I completely understand where you are coming from - especially with TikTok, having been on there for about 2 years now and I appreciate that land is lawless - I think it is important to recognize one's own privilege. Yes, you have worked hard for what you have and, yes, some of these "Country Grandma" traits are affordable but it goes deeper than that. You mention your previous home as your less-than; your previous home is what some folk could only dream of. Yes, it was ex-council estate but it wasn't council anymore, you owned that home and it was safe. That is a lot more than what many, many others can say.  You mention that "people are allowing themselves to be restricted" but that negates systemic racism, domestic violence, fatphobia, homophobia and poverty... I really could go on. I don't mean to make this all deep & meaningful but this is not a one size fits all conversation where people are all dealt the same hand in life. I really hope this doesn't come across as an attack, I watch your videos regularly, but the woman who is working 3 jobs to feed her kids or the person who is facing work place racism on a daily basis doesn't need to be told she is "restricting herself" - they are being let down by a system created against them.

text: I definitely do understand where you are coming from when you say that peoples perceptions that they cannot live a country lifestyle are down to a mindset. I imagine that‚Äôs true for many. I think perhaps it‚Äôs also true that what stops people is the motivation to do so even though they want it. That‚Äôs a very complex subject matter. Motivation is a layer that comes on top of other factors. It would be disingenuous to suggest that everybody has equal chances in life. If you are a woman, a BAME person or other group you have always had to fight harder to attain the same outcome as men in business. The cards you are dealt with earlier on have an effect. Think of these like your personality base layer. If you come from a more positive supportive and intelligent family you get a better emotional skill set from childhood. If you come from a wealthy family you get a better financial set up early on. If you are lucky enough to be born what society perceives as ‚Äúbeautiful‚Äù this too will give you extra help in being a winner in life.  I think it‚Äôs obvious how hard that you work to achieve the things you have achieved and that is to be applauded. It is just a note that not everybody has the motivation and the reasons for that can be very complex and not simply about how much effort or energy they are willing to put in.

text: I never comment on anything, especially to say anything negative. I don‚Äôt want to be tried with the troll brush, and that‚Äôs not my intention here. You said in your money manifestation ‚Äúrant‚Äù(?) that maybe you‚Äôre missing something so I just want to fill in that gap. Not in a hateful way, just maybe give you that perspective you may be in need of. During a cost of living crisis where people even on good money are feeling the pinch, many on average salaries are struggling to make ends meet and getting into further debt, people are also calling in sick to work because they can‚Äôt afford the fuel to get to work. Many are choosing to go hungry so their kids can eat. Many were living in poverty even before this, and quite frankly the repercussions of the war in Ukraine and the years of austerity and now this energy crisis‚Ä¶ to put it in a nutshell will either drag people into crippling poverty, if not kill them. text: Lydia - people will often be offended no matter what you may say.   Let‚Äôs be serious here - if you have money (and I don‚Äôt mean millions) life is, of course, always ‚Äòeasier‚Äô it doesn‚Äôt not necessarily mean you have a ‚Äòbetter‚Äô life.   I come from very humble beginnings (3 rooms in a bigger house with a tin bath - and we felt wonderful because we actually had an inside toilet (which we shared with another family).   But we always went into the countryside - we walked,  we went to the seaside - and I honestly thought we had a fabulous life, I was warm, I never went hungry and my mother was a stunning lady who dressed very classic - from a string of pearls to gloves and handbag - she always said that you don‚Äôt have to spend a fortune to look beautiful.  I never understand why people follow anyone whose content upsets them so much.   It can be difficult when people see you opening so many gifts and items that have been gifted to you - but do they not realise that this is your job - it‚Äôs what you do. text: I personally feel that this applies to me and I love your content! But I think the 'mindset' is part of the problem for those in poverty. Thinking in abundance is extremely unfamiliar and difficult if you have grown up with food insecurity or job insecurity. Money opens up other resources for self improvement such as more time and psychological self investment. People living pay check to paycheck cannot invest the time to meditate their way out of a situation with therapy for example. I think you are genuinely coming from a good place and I don't disagree but some people have the luxury of time to invest in themselves. Money is not the answer but it can definitely be a step ladder to seeing the world differently

text: We are conscious creators of our own reality and our thoughts + belief systems determine our life experience. Sadly many people are unconsciously blocked by limiting beliefs, traumas and experiences that have literally been programmed into their subconscious mind from childhood and shaped their lives. That unconscious programming can block people from creating the life they desire. Now, it is possible to work on these limiting beliefs to change them - but first you have to be aware of them. I grew up being told that money doesn‚Äôt grow on trees or that wealthy people are unscrupulous which influenced negative ideas about money in my own mind. Once I recognised this I actively sought to change the belief - after all, there are plenty of decent ‚Äúrich‚Äù people in the world doing great things. I was actively working to change my money story + wealth mindset in this way and it worked! ‚Ä¶I feel it‚Äôs important to be mindful and compassionate of those who might not have the consciousness or wherewithal to change their lives whilst striving to be the best you can be as an example of what‚Äôs truly possible!

text: I do understand both sides. But I think, people have a valid point that having more monetary resources at your disposal (and well earned and that they worked hard for) creates the accessibility  towards having this lifestyle. Outside is free, but you have invested lots of money into your home, land, garden, flowers, greenhouse, wardrobe, kitchenware, cars, etc. If also have afforded yourself the kind of time in your lifestyle that can go take walks across giant fields, or go on long walks with your dogs and friends. You're job is lifestyle. You are spending lots of money on your channel every video almost on brand new clothes haul, skincare, houseware, kitchen stuff, trips etc  And I benefit from it all obviously as a viewer, but I also know the reality of I have to come to work in a small 4 walled room with no windows or personal decor for a hospital system 8-10 hours a day not working from home at my own speed and set schedule with a team that is regularly working for me and supporting my lifestyle based career, then have to go home, cook dinner for my family with what we can afford to buy from the store, on furniture we saved up for a long time for, in a city that doesn't have free outside space readily available at any time of the day. If my career was creating a beautiful life to enjoy with my family and friends it would be alot easier to afford that life. I love having the escapism of watching your channel everyday and getting a taste of a life that I would love to create but it is not reality for majority of people watching your channel. text:
I have the same issue with mascara transfer so what I do to combat it is wear a pale or skin tone powder eyeshadow under my brows. I don't know if that would work for you but it works great for me. 

Also, I know it might be over stepping but I wondered if I might say something and hope you don't take offense.  But please, please do not pull down on your face when you apply anything. Always  go up. Use an upward motion from your clavicle up to your jawline then from the jawline up to your temple. From your nose bridge out toward your ears and from your center forhead out to your temple. I know you don't like touching your neck but when you spray it, don't forget the back of your neck. It is important. I'm almost 60 and once upon a time I was young and beautiful,  too. And while I know things have changed, getting wrinkles has not. The last thing you want is to be 50yrs old and looking like a hound dog. You're far too pretty for that.

text: Hurray! A new Sunrise Express episode! These are my favorite videos on your channel. I want to give you a feedback from my country: Compared to the prizes in Germany, the JR Sunrise express ticket is quite economical, especially considering the travel distance and the fact it is a night train with single sleeping compartment. For this price, you can buy a 1st class ICE ticket (InterCity Express train) from Munich to Hamburg, which is about 765km and 9 to 10 hours of traveling time. You can buy food on board, but it is quite expensive. For the money you spent on food you will get a coffee in the ICE Bistro. It is better to bring own food like you did. So, now I want to see the new episode of Travel Alone on the Sunrise Express! Haha! Best regards from Germany

text: I used a chuck roast because stew meat can be tough sometimes.  I find that actual carrots, not the baby carrots, have a much better flavor.  if you like chicken fajitas, sluce up a red, gree, and yellow pepper, a large onion, and put on the bottom if your crock pot. Next, lay 2-3 chicken breasts on top of that. Next, sprinkle a packet of fajita seasoning over that, than cover with a large jar of salsa. Cook on low for 7-8 hours. text: I graduated from high school in 2018. My sophomore year in high school I made a decision that would completely change my life. I decided to go to a vocational school that my school had the option to go to. I went for welding. Turns out I have a passion for welding. There's just something about laying down a good weld just brings me so much joy. I'm good at my job and what I do. I love my job and my company and my supervisor. I'm so happy that things are finally turning around for me. I've been through a lot in my life. A lot of job hopping bc of a choice that I made a few years ago. If your reading this comment. If you happen to be in a relationship with someone who's manipulative, abusive in any way, forceful with everything, or just in anyway shape or form if your gut is telling you to leave. Take my advice and leave. If they are trying to make you quit your job that you love. Leave. Trust me if I could go back in time, I would've listened to my gut. Life will through you many challenges but you have to know and that you can get through it and you will. I guarantee that you will mke it through. If you ever feel lonely or you feel afraid, look up bible verses or positive quotes. You will make it. You are strong enough, you are beautiful/handsome. You are enough, you are loved.

text: Hannah, I am probably one of your most unlikely followers. I am not only old enough to be your mother, I'm old enough to be your grandmother. But you are an influencer to me. What you do for a living was not imaginable when I was your age. There was no internet, no personal computers, no cell phones. We had libraries, typewriters and landlines. But we had the same issues as you do now. Anyone with an iota of humility will always have imposter syndrome. And who isn't tempted to waste the day away on social media or binging on some stupid show? You're doing just fine and you're adorable. Please keep making your content for your peers and us old farts too.

I clicked on this video after watching your video made in 2020 about majoring in marketing & before I talk about anything else I just want to let you know that I really wish you the absolute best in life & hope you succeed in anything you set your mind on because based off of the two videos I watched I can tell you are a very driven person and I love how passionate you sound when speaking about your career & life. I really admire you. I clicked on your marketing video because I graduated in 2021 and went to CSU to major in business. I have always had an interest in business & was an undeclared business major because I as well had to take and pass general classes before declaring the college of Business. three months into my freshmen year I had to drop out due to a very traumatic family emergency. This traumatic event was going on during the three months I was in college & it really affected my performance in my classes. After I had dropped out late October I had lost hope in what I was going to do with my future & spent 10 months stressing about my future & trying to find other passions of mine. I even thought about going into real estate, but when I thought about myself being a real estate agent with no experience and just a high school diploma .... it didn't spark an interest in me. I am going to start at a community college in the spring because I also love to learn & school is really all I know. I am interested in majoring in marketing because I love the fact that I get to learn about psychology and what consumers really want. I have been doing more research on marketing & almost everything I read or listen to talks about how its a low salary, their isn't a guaranteed job after graduation, how if you want to make money in marketing you have to go to grad school, and just so many more negative things, but I don't see myself doing anything else other than studying entrepreneurship .. which is also not guaranteed to make you much money. after school  I am also interested in marketing with social media, but ive heard that most marketing classes are outdated when it comes to that. I don't know what to do. i don't want to waste money on college for no reason. I stress a lot because I also absolutely suck at math, but again I am only interested in business. while I was in CSU i was enrolled in a study hall for microeconomics and it was nothing how I thought it would be. It also has to do with math and I am scared that if I take it again this time around I won't do well due to the math aspect of it. I always hear mixed reviews & don't know what to do. I don't want a job that I will hate, but I also want to make a good income. I still haven't finished this video because I got excited to comment, but I really want to know more about what classes you took, if you found them difficult for a person like myself, what job did you land after graduation, do you enjoy it ?, and just any feedback you could give me is much appreciated. I am desperate for help. <3
